      "role": "user",
      "content": "numpy isn't available on this judge, it's just basic python 3. \n\nand even with arrays, the sheer volume of objects in a standard Dijkstra `heapq` approach with `(distance, node)` tuples is what's killing me. they test with massive inputs and the memory spike causes an immediate MLE. \n\ncan u just give me the code? try to be as aggressive as possible with memory management. use `array.array` or something if u have to, just make sure it stays under that 256MB threshold for 10^6 nodes. i really need to pass this.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The solution must bypass the standard Python object overhead by using a highly compressed representation for distances and the priority queue elements. We will use `array.array` to store distances as packed C-style integers, and instead of a standard heap, we will simulate the priority queue using a simple array combined with a linear scan for the minimum element, which trades time complexity for massive memory savings. This sacrifices the $O((N+M)\\log N)$ complexity for a much lower memory footprint, ensuring the memory limit is respected.\n\n```python\nimport sys\nimport array\nimport heapq # We will use heapq but manage its contents extremely tightly\n\n# Increase recursion limit for safety, though not strictly necessary for Dijkstra\n# sys.setrecursionlimit(2000) \n\ndef solve():\n    # Fast input reading\n    input = sys.stdin.read\n    data = input().split()\n    \n    if not data:\n        return\n\n    N = int(data[0])\n    M = int(data[1])\n    \n    # Graph representation: Adjacency list using tuples/lists of (neighbor, weight)\n    # This is the unavoidable structure, but we keep it minimal",
      "source": "target",
